### ‚úÖ Standard Cost Notations:

| Symbol | Name                   | Description                                                  |
| ------ | ---------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **C‚ÇÅ** | Holding/Carrying Cost  | Cost to hold one unit of inventory per unit of time.         |
| **C‚ÇÇ** | Shortage/Stockout Cost | Cost incurred when inventory is insufficient to meet demand. |
| **C‚ÇÉ** | Ordering/Setup Cost    | Fixed cost per order, regardless of quantity ordered.        |

---

### üîÑ Occasionally Seen or Custom Notations:

While **C‚ÇÅ to C‚ÇÉ** are **standard and widely accepted**, some textbooks or authors **extend the notation** further to **C‚ÇÑ, C‚ÇÖ, etc.** to cover more specific or advanced situations. These are not always standard but may represent:

| Symbol | Possible Meaning (Context-Dependent) |
| ------ | ------------------------------------ |
| **C‚ÇÑ** | Purchase cost per unit               |
| **C‚ÇÖ** | Transportation or delivery cost      |
| **C‚ÇÜ** | Inspection cost per unit             |
| **C‚Çá** | Obsolescence or deterioration cost   |

> ‚ö†Ô∏è **Important:** Not all sources use the same labels. **C‚ÇÑ onwards is not universal**, so always check your specific textbook or exam material.

---

### üìå Summary:

* **C‚ÇÅ, C‚ÇÇ, C‚ÇÉ** are **core** in classical EOQ and inventory models.
* **C‚ÇÑ and beyond** are **occasionally used** in advanced or customized models.
* Stick to **C‚ÇÅ = holding**, **C‚ÇÇ = shortage**, **C‚ÇÉ = ordering** for your standard problems unless your syllabus specifies otherwise.
